{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638348","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638348"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:52:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:52:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17703"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17703","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17703"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10417"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72031"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10417","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10417"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17703"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57501"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"10429"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24328"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24340"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72031","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72031"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ERhodopsin is the primary photopigment found in rod photoreceptor cells of the retina. It plays a crucial role in vision under low light conditions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the initial molecular event when light strikes rhodopsin?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Activation of cyclic guanosine monophosphate","Release of calcium from intracellular stores","Conversion of 11-cis retinal to all-trans retinal","Opening of sodium channels","Separation of opsin from retinal"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen light strikes rhodopsin, the \u003Cstrong\u003Econversion of 11-cis retinal to all-trans retinal\u003C/strong\u003E occurs. This conformational change in the retinal molecule causes subsequent dissociation of rhodopsin and triggers the phototransduction cascade.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivation of cyclic guanosine monophosphate\u003C/strong\u003E occurs as a downstream effect and is actually decreased during the cascade rather than being the initial event.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERelease of calcium from intracellular stores\u003C/strong\u003E is a later consequence of the phototransduction cascade, not the initial molecular event.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpening of sodium channels\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as these channels actually close during phototransduction as a downstream effect.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeparation of opsin from retinal\u003C/strong\u003E occurs after the initial conformational change of retinal, not as the first event in the cascade.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter retinal undergoes this conformational change, the activated rhodopsin stimulates the G-protein transducin, which then activates phosphodiesterase, leading to closure of sodium channels and hyperpolarisation of the rod cell.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Rhodopsin consists of the protein opsin bound to retinal, a vitamin A derivative.","Light causes retinal to change from 11-cis to all-trans configuration, leading to rhodopsin dissociation.","The phototransduction cascade begins when activated rhodopsin stimulates transducin."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57501"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17703"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57501","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57501"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T21:17:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T21:18:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10417"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72031"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4942","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4942"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\u2699\ufe0f","name":"Physiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-